00:00:32.960 --> 00:00:39.400
So remember, yesterday we saw the topic yesterday

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:40.480
was dot product.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:46.860
And remember, the definition of dot product,

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:50.320
well, the dot product of two vectors

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:55.960
is obtained by multiplying the first component

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:57.920
with the first component, the second with the second,

00:00:57.960 --> 00:00:58.580
and so on.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:00.460
And summing these, and you get the scalar.

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:03.860
And the geometric interpretation of that

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:08.200
is that you can also take the length of A,

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:10.720
take the length of B, multiply them,

00:01:11.240 --> 00:01:13.860
and multiply that by the cosine of the angle

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:15.380
between the two vectors.

00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:24.960
So we've seen several applications of that.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.440
So one application is to find lengths and angles.

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:52.340
So for example, well, you can use this relation to give you

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:55.260
that the cosine of the angle between two vectors

00:01:56.140 --> 00:02:01.360
is the dot product divided by the product of the length.

00:02:05.380 --> 00:02:11.360
Another application that we have is to detect

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:16.140
whether two vectors are perpendicular.

00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:20.220
So to decide if two vectors are perpendicular to each other,

00:02:20.420 --> 00:02:23.680
all we have to do is compute that dot product.

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:26.020
And see if we get zero.

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:32.340
OK.

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:40.840
And well, one third application that we didn't have time

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:43.780
to discuss yesterday, that I will mention very quickly,

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:52.040
is to find components of, so let's say,

00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:56.460
we find the component of a vector A along a direction,

00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:02.960
u, so some unit vector.

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:05.060
So let me explain.

00:03:07.460 --> 00:03:10.060
Let's say that I have some direction.

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:13.380
For example, the horizontal axis on this blackboard,

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:15.080
but it could be any direction in space.

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:18.080
And to describe this direction, maybe I

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:21.860
have a unit vector along this axis.

00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:28.320
Let's say that I have any other vector A,

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:32.540
and I want to find out what is the component of a along u.

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:38.560
So that means what is the length of this projection of a

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:40.260
to the given direction?

00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:41.860
OK.

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:51.920
So this thing here is the component of a along u.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:55.960
Well, how do we find that?

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:03.220
Well, we know that here we have a right angle.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:10.040
So this component is just length a times cosine of the angle,

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:10.960
between a and u.

00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:15.440
But now that means actually we can compute it very easily,

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:22.380
because, well, I could, you know, that's the same as length a

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:26.440
times length u times cosine theta, because u is a unit vector.

00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:31.360
It's a unit vector, that means this is equal to 1.

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:37.840
And so that's the same as the dot product between a and u.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:40.320
OK.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:41.760
So that's very easy.

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:46.000
And of course, the most obvious cases of that is, say,

00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:48.640
for example, we want us to find the component along i hat,

00:04:48.800 --> 00:04:52.300
the first axis, you know, the unit vector along the x axis.

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:56.500
Then you do the dot product with i hat, which is 1,00,

00:04:56.940 --> 00:04:58.540
what you get is the first component.

00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:01.000
And that's indeed the x component of the vector.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:03.480
Similarly, say you want the z component,

00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:06.160
you do the dot product with k, that gives you

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:07.800
the last component of your vector.

00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:14.460
But the same works with a unit vector in any direction.

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:18.080
So what's an application of that?

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:26.140
Well, for example, in physics, maybe you

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:32.120
have seen situations where you have a pendulum that swings.

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:35.520
So you have maybe some mass at the end of a string.

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:40.300
And that mass swings back and forth on a circle.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:43.680
And to analyze this mechanically, you

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:46.120
want to use, of course, Newton's laws of mechanics.

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:50.240
And you want to use, well, you know, forces and so on.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:54.920
But I claim that components of vectors

00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:58.540
are useful here to understand what happens geometrically.

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:03.940
So what other forces exerted on this pendulum?

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:10.280
Well, there's its weight, which usually points downwards.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:15.500
And there's the tension of the string.

00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:27.360
And these two forces together are what explains how this pendulum

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:29.200
is going to move back and forth.

00:06:30.940 --> 00:06:35.320
Now, you could try to understand the equations of mothin

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:38.320
using xy coordinates, or maybe xz, or whatever

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:39.900
you want to call them, let's say xy.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:45.880
But really, what causes the pendulum to swing back and forth

00:06:46.580 --> 00:06:49.840
and also to somehow stay at constant distance,

00:06:50.600 --> 00:06:54.840
are phenomena relative to this circular trajectory.

00:06:55.920 --> 00:06:59.400
So for example, maybe instead of taking components

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.740
along the x and y axis, we want to look at two other unit

00:07:03.740 --> 00:07:04.100
vectors.

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:09.680
So we can look at a vector, let's call it t,

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:13.140
that's tangent to the trajectory.

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:18.040
So I can you read that?

00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:19.000
Maybe it's not very readable.

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:28.620
T is tangent to the trajectory.

00:07:32.340 --> 00:07:37.040
And on the other hand, we can introduce another vector.

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:39.360
Let's call that n.

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:48.120
And that one is normal perpendicular to the trajectory.

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:54.840
And so now, if you think about it,

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:58.020
you can look at the components of the weight

00:07:59.300 --> 00:08:01.980
along the tangent direction and along the normal direction.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:15.840
And so the component of f along the tangent direction

00:08:16.900 --> 00:08:20.060
is what causes acceleration in the direction

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:20.860
along the trajectory.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:23.420
It's what causes the pendulum to swing back and forth.

00:08:37.120 --> 00:08:41.580
And the component along n on the other hand.

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:49.720
So that's the part of the weight that tends to pull our mass

00:08:49.720 --> 00:08:53.900
away from this point is what's going to be responsible

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:55.520
for the tension of the string.

00:08:56.080 --> 00:09:00.500
It's why the string is stowed and not actually slack

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:02.840
and with things moving all over the place.

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:12.540
So that one is responsible for the tension of the string.

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:20.160
And now, of course, if you want to compute things,

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:22.500
well, maybe you will call this angle theta

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:25.640
and then you will express things explicitly using signs

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:28.080
and cosines and you will solve for the equations of motion.

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:31.040
Okay, that would be a very interesting physics problem,

