00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:11.260
One important concept that we haven't understood yet

00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:14.160
in terms of vectors is Aria.

00:10:16.940 --> 00:10:23.840
So let's say that we want to find the Aria of this pentagon.

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:27.660
Well, how do we compute that using vectors?

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:29.000
Can we do it using vectors?

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:31.540
Yes, we can.

00:10:32.100 --> 00:10:33.920
And that's going to be the goal, but how?

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:41.420
So the first thing we should do is probably simplify the problem.

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:44.340
You know, we don't actually need to bother with pentagons,

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:46.020
or we need to know our triangles.

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:50.240
Because for example, you can cut that into three triangles

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:52.800
and then some Aria of the triangles.

00:10:53.840 --> 00:11:02.340
Okay, so perhaps easier, what's the Aria of a triangle?

00:11:05.260 --> 00:11:07.660
So let's start with a triangle in the plane.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:13.980
And well, then we need two vectors to describe it.

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:16.280
Say, A and B here.

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:19.860
How do we find the Aria of a triangle?

00:11:20.580 --> 00:11:23.240
Well, we all know base times height of R2.

00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:25.060
So what's the base?

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:25.700
What's the height?

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:34.360
Well, so the Aria of this triangle is going to be one half of the base

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:37.800
is going to be the length of A and the height.

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:43.540
Well, if you call theta this angle, then this is length B sine theta.

00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:52.660
Now, that looks a lot like the formula we had there,

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:54.280
except for one little catch.

00:11:54.420 --> 00:11:55.800
This is a sine instead of a cosine.

00:11:57.660 --> 00:11:58.900
How do we deal with that?

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:07.000
Well, what we could do is first find the cosine of the angle.

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:09.900
We know how to find the cosine of the angle using that product.

00:12:13.540 --> 00:12:19.200
Then solve for sine using sine square plus cosine square

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:20.820
equals one.

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:23.800
And then plug that back into here.

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:28.480
Well, that works, but it's kind of a very complicated way of doing it.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:29.520
So that's an easier way.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:31.580
And that's going to be determinants.

00:12:31.720 --> 00:12:34.740
But let me explain how we get to that.

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:39.020
Maybe still doing elementary geometry and dot products first.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:49.360
So let's see.

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:55.200
What we can do is instead of finding the sine of theta,

00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:57.120
well, we're not good at finding signs of angles,

00:12:57.300 --> 00:12:59.420
but we are very good now at finding cosines of angles.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:05.000
So maybe we can find another angle whose cosine is the same as the sine of theta.

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:08.660
Well, you probably heard about complementary angles.

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:17.520
And how, if I take my vector A, if I have my vector B here, I have an angle theta.

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:24.660
Well, let's say that I rotate my vector A by 90 degrees to get a new vector A prime.

00:13:26.180 --> 00:13:34.640
So A prime is just A rotated by 90 degrees.

00:13:35.820 --> 00:13:39.860
Then the angle between these two guys, let's say theta prime,

00:13:41.980 --> 00:13:47.880
well, theta prime is 90 degrees or pi over 2 radians minus theta.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:53.800
So in particular, cosine of theta prime is equal to sine of theta.

00:13:57.800 --> 00:14:07.780
So in particular, that means that length A, length B sine theta,

00:14:08.220 --> 00:14:12.660
which is what we would need to know in order to find the area of this triangle,

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:17.960
is equal to, well, A and A prime have the same length.

00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:20.420
So let me replace that by length of A prime.

00:14:20.420 --> 00:14:22.000
I'm not changing anything.

00:14:22.940 --> 00:14:25.800
Length B cosine theta prime.

00:14:28.120 --> 00:14:34.140
And now we have something that's much easier, of course, because that's just A prime dot B.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:38.580
So that looks like a very good plan.

00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:43.820
There's only one small thing which is we don't know yet how to find this A prime.

00:14:44.580 --> 00:14:47.500
Well, I claim it's not very hard.

00:14:49.080 --> 00:14:49.720
Let's see.

00:14:51.580 --> 00:14:54.500
Why don't you guys do the hard work?

00:14:55.400 --> 00:15:01.980
So let's say that I have a plane vector A with two components, A1, A2,

00:15:02.420 --> 00:15:05.340
and I want to rotate it counterclockwise by 90 degrees.

00:15:08.220 --> 00:15:11.940
So it looks like maybe we should change some signs somewhere,

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:13.500
maybe we should do something with a component.

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:20.220
Can you come up with an idea of what it might be?

00:15:27.620 --> 00:15:33.800
Okay, so I see a lot of people answering three.

00:15:34.700 --> 00:15:39.280
I see some other answers, but the majority vote seems to be number three.

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:43.360
Minus A2 and A1.

00:15:44.300 --> 00:15:45.280
I think I agree.

00:15:46.240 --> 00:15:46.620
So let's see.

00:15:49.280 --> 00:16:03.440
Let's say that we have this vector A with components A1, so A1 is here and A2.

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:04.400
So A2 is here.

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:08.340
Okay, let's rotate this box by 90 degrees counterclockwise.

00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:19.040
So this rectangular box ends up there, it's the same box, just flitting it side.

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:25.660
So this length here becomes A1 and this length here becomes A2.

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:28.580
And that means our new vector A prime

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:36.840
is going to be, well, the first component looks like an A2,

00:16:37.060 --> 00:16:41.500
but it's pointing to the left when A2 is positive, so it's minus A2.

00:16:43.420 --> 00:16:48.860
And the Y component is going to be the same as this guy, so it's going to be A1.

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:56.980
If you wanted instead to rotate clockwise, then you would do the opposite.

00:16:56.980 --> 00:16:58.880
You would do A2 minus A1.

00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:03.760
Okay, is that reasonably clear for everyone?

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:13.580
Okay, so, well, let's continue at calculation there.

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:20.040
A prime we've decided is minus A2 from A1.

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:27.680
So minus A2, A1, dot product with, let's call B1 and B2, the components of B,

00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:36.140
then that will be, well, minus A2, B1 plus A1, B2.

00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:37.720
Let me write that the other way around.

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:40.220
A1, B2, minus A2, B1.

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:52.000
And that's a quantity that you may already know, and of the name of determinant of vectors A and B,

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:58.640
which we've write symbolically using this notation.

00:17:58.880 --> 00:18:05.560
So we put A and B next to each other inside a 2x2 table, and we put this vertical bars,

00:18:05.560 --> 00:18:12.340
and that means the determinant of these numbers, it means this guy times this guy,

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:14.300
minus this guy times this guy.

00:18:15.660 --> 00:18:18.920
Okay, so that's called the determinant.

00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:36.600
And geometrically what it measures is the area, well, not of a triangle,

00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:40.880
because we didn't divide by 2, but of a parallelogram formed by A and B.

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:50.800
So it measures the area of the parallelogram with sides A and B.

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:55.540
And of course, if you want the triangle, then you will just divide by 2.

00:18:55.900 --> 00:18:57.720
Okay, the triangle is half the parallelogram.

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:01.440
There's one small catch.

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:05.000
The area usually is something that's going to be positive.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:11.460
This guy here has no reason to be positive or negative, because in fact,

00:19:14.980 --> 00:19:25.940
well, if you compute things, you will see that whether it's positive or negative depends on whether A and B are clockwise or counterclockwise from each other.

00:19:25.940 --> 00:19:32.860
I mean, the issue that we have, well, when we say the area is one half length A, length B, sine theta,

00:19:33.740 --> 00:19:37.340
that was assuming that theta is positive, that its sine is positive.

00:19:37.620 --> 00:19:42.560
Otherwise, if theta is negative, maybe we need to take the absolute value of this.

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:49.700
So just to be more thoughtful, I will say the determinant is either plus or minus the area.

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:58.000
Okay, any questions about this?

00:20:01.220 --> 00:20:03.460
Yes?

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:16.220
Oh, sorry, that's not a dot product. That's a usual multiplication.

00:20:17.120 --> 00:20:21.580
Okay? That's a length A times length B times sine theta.

00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:29.340
And so that's equal to the area of the parallelogram.

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:33.000
So, let me explain that again.

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:44.820
So if I have two vectors A and B, so I can form a parallelogram with them, I can form a triangle.

00:20:45.820 --> 00:20:59.640
And so the area of the parallelogram is equal to length A, length B sine theta, is equal to the determinant of A and B.

00:21:01.840 --> 00:21:09.900
While the area of a triangle is one half of that.

00:21:21.020 --> 00:21:24.880
And again, to be thoughtful, I should say, these things can be positive or negative.

00:21:25.880 --> 00:21:33.220
So depending on whether you can't fangle positively or negatively, you will get either the area or minus the area.

00:21:33.380 --> 00:21:36.720
The area is actually the absolute value of this quantity.

00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:40.140
Okay, is that clearer?

00:21:43.780 --> 00:21:44.020
Okay.

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:49.020
Yes?

00:21:49.780 --> 00:21:49.780


00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:59.960
So if you want to compute the area, you will just take the absolute value of a determinant.

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:06.960
Okay? So, our area will be...

00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:18.080
Well, I should say the area of the parallelogram, so that it's completely clear.

00:22:20.140 --> 00:22:22.060
Sorry. You have a question?

00:22:31.660 --> 00:22:33.520
Explain again. Sorry. Let's have a question.

00:22:33.660 --> 00:22:35.920
How the determinant equals the area of the parallelogram?

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:43.100
Okay. So the area of the parallelogram, it's going to be the base times the height.

00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:50.920
So the base, let's take this guy to be the base, so the length of the base will be length of A.

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:57.740
And the height will be obtained by ticking B, but only looking at the vertical part.

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:01.400
So that will be length of B times the sine of theta.

00:23:02.420 --> 00:23:06.820
Okay, so that's how I got the area of the parallelogram is length A, length B sine theta.

